training_organizations.name: Delaware DSCYF – Training Unit
training_organizations.description: Delaware’s Department of Services for Children, Youth & Their Families runs a training unit that prepares child welfare caseworkers and investigators. The unit provides instruction on Delaware’s policies, the legal framework (e.g. DFS involvement in Family Court), and skills like risk assessment and case planning.

training_organizations.name: Children & Families First Delaware
training_organizations.description: A nonprofit agency that partners with Delaware’s child welfare system to provide a variety of services. It manages programs like foster parent recruitment and training, in-home parenting education, and mental health services for families involved with CPS – helping ensure families can access needed supports to keep children safe.

training_organizations.name: Evident Change (Structured Decision Making)
training_organizations.description: Delaware’s Division of Family Services has implemented the Structured Decision Making model from Evident Change to guide safety and risk assessments in CPS cases. This nonprofit provides the state with standardized assessment tools and training to improve decision-making consistency when evaluating child abuse/neglect referrals:contentReference[oaicite:1]{index=1}:contentReference[oaicite:2]{index=2}.

policies.TribalFoster: No, Tribes within state do not provide foster care
policies.ReportAnonymous: General public (not mandated reporters) can remain anonymous
policies.FatalitiesReview: Yes, reviews are required for all or some cases
policies.Def_Subtype_Abuse: Physical abuse includes providing illegal substance to child, involving child in physical domestic violence altercations, and female genital mutilation; Sexual abuse includes child pornography
policies.Def_Subtype_Neglect: Neglect includes malnourishment, lack of shelter, educational neglect, medical neglect, parental substance misuse, failure to provide supervision, failure to protect from trafficking, and exploitation
policies.NearFatalitiesReview: Yes, reviews are required for all or some cases
policies.ScreenReq_OtherSpecify: Substance abuse and domestic violence screening
policies.AntiDiscrim_OtherSpecify: Any other category protected by state or federal laws
policies.DefAge_VaryByTypeSpecify: Sexual abuse applies when the child is younger than age 14 and the alleged perpetrator is an adult age 19 or older or when the child is younger than age 16 and the alleged perpetrator is an adult who is at least 10 years older than the child
policies.DefPerp_VaryByTypeSpecify: For sexual abuse, there is no requirement for the perpetrator to have care, custody or control of the child, which is required for other types of maltreatment
policies.InvestQual_TrainingSpecify: Division of Family Services (DFS) new worker training
policies.InvestQual_ExperienceSpecify: 1) No experience required if individual possesses a bachelor's degree or higher, or has an anticipated graduation date within 3 months, with coursework in behavioral science, psychology, sociology, human services or related field; 2) One year of experience in professional health or human service work is required for individuals without a bachelor's degree or higher, or an anticipated graduation date within 3 months, with coursework in behavioral science, psychology, sociology, human services or related field; 3) Two years of experience in paraprofessional health or human service work is required for individuals without a bachelor's degree or higher, or an anticipated graduation date within 3 months, with coursework in behavioral science, psychology, sociology, human services or related field (an Associate's degree may substitute for one year of paraprofessional experience).
policies.ScreenerQual_TrainingSpecify: Division of Family Services (DFS) new worker training
policies.InvestReq_MHEvalCases_Specify: Severe mental health cases; Cases in which allegations involve a life-threatening mental health condition and require evaluation/intervention

policies.InvestReq_MedEvalCases_Specify: Physical abuse where there is an injury or illness
